mium—further influencing the final payout. However, regardless of the option, unpaid loans always reduce the net benefit, making loan management essential for maximizing beneficiary payouts [Data: Entities (32, 50), Relationships (49, 68, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Interest impacts loan balance and account value dynamics\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Interest may be paid annually or added to the loan balance, directly affecting the total loan amount and the policy’s financial structure. When interest is added to the loan, it increases the outstanding balance, which in turn reduces the account value and future surrender value. This compounding effect can erode the policy’s cash value over time if loans are not managed carefully. Conversely, interest earned on the account value can support growth, especially when premiums are allocated to investment options. The interplay between interest on loans and interest earned on the account value shapes the long-term financial trajectory of the policy [Data: Entities (54), Relationships (73, 68, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Lapse occurs due to non-payment during grace period\",\n            \"explanation\": \"A policy lapses when sufficient premium is not received within the 61-day grace period, resulting in termination of coverage. The lapse is governed by FlexProtect Insurance Solutions’ rules and triggers automatic payment of the excess account value over surrender charges. This outcome underscores the importance of timely premium payments and the risks associated with relying solely on account value to cover charges. Once a policy lapses, reinstatement may require additional underwriting, proof of insurability, and payment of accrued fees or interest, making it a complex and often costly process [Data: Entities (51), Relationships (62, 26, +more)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Chief Executive Officer as authorized signatory\",\